\par
Abstract The thermodynamic theory of dislocation/grain boundary interaction, including dislocation pileup\par
against, absorption by, and transfer through the grain boundary, is developed for non-uniform plastic deforma-\par
tions in polycrystals. The case study is carried out on the boundary conditions affecting work hardening of a\par
bicrystal subjected to plane constrained shear for three types of grain boundaries: (i) impermeable hard grain\par
boundary, (ii) grain boundary that allows dislocation transfer without absorption, and (iii) grain boundary that\par
absorbs dislocations and allows them to pass later.\par
\par
Keywords Thermodynamics \u183? Dislocations \u183? Grain boundary \u183? Polycrystals \u183? Work hardening\par
\par
\par
1 Introduction\par
\par
The interaction between dislocations and grain boundaries plays an essential role in the mechanical response\par
of polycrystalline materials to loading. Several outcomes of this interaction are possible. At low dislocation\par
density, the grain boundary blocks the movement of dislocations and forces them to pileup against it, with the by-\par
product of linearly increased kinematic work hardening. As the dislocation density exceeds some critical value,\par
a certain amount of dislocations is absorbed by the grain boundary, causing an increase in the surface dislocation\par
density and the misorientation between adjacent grains. Dislocations can also be emitted at a later stage of\par
straining in the neighboring grain or transferred through the grain boundary. In the presence of grain boundaries,\par
non-uniform plastic deformation occurs, leading to non-redundant (geometrically necessary) dislocations, so\par
the need for continuum models that include the gradient of plastic deformation becomes evident. Berdichevsky\par
and Sedov [1] were the first to introduce the curl of plastic deformation (Nye\u8211?Bilby\u8211?Kr\u246?ner\u8217?s tensor) into the\par
continuum dislocation theory (CDT) and associate it with the density of non-redundant dislocations. They\par
also proposed the thermodynamics of dislocations, using this density of non-redundant dislocations as a state\par
variable in the free energy and giving the variational formulation of CDT (see the further developments in\par
[2,3]). The main drawback of this thermodynamic approach is the absence of configurational entropy and\par
its dual quantity, the effective temperature of dislocations, introduced a few decades later by Langer et al.\par
[4]. Together with the density of redundant dislocations, this configurational entropy enables ones to build\par
up the meaningful thermodynamics of dislocations satisfying two universal laws for plastic flows discovered\par
in [5,6]. Recently, one of us extended CDT by introducing the density of redundant dislocations as well\par
as the configurational entropy as additional state variables [7]. He has shown that the new theory, called\par
thermodynamic dislocation theory (TDT), can predict both kinematic and isotropic work hardening. This TDT\par
has been applied to model grain boundaries as hard obstacles that block dislocations, leading to dislocation\par
