pileup, kinematic work hardening, and Bauschinger effect [8,9]. Piao and Le [10] further applied the theory to\par
the problem of interaction between screw dislocations and permeable grain boundary based on the experiments\par
performed by Kondo et al. [11]. There, an interfacial dissipation potential is proposed and additional boundary\par
conditions for the grain boundary are derived to model screw dislocation/grain boundary interaction.\par
     Alternative phenomenological models that include the interaction between dislocations and grain bound-\par
aries have been proposed in the context of strain gradient plasticity by Fleck et al. [12]; Aifantis [13]; Gao et al.\par
[14]; Gurtin [15], and a large number of investigations have been carried out within this approach. Fredriksson\par
and Gudmundson [16] proposed an energetic model according to which the plastic work is stored as interfacial\par
energy that depends on the jump of plastic slip at the grain boundary, while Fleck and Willis [17] argued that\par
material hardening due to the grain boundary is mainly carried by energy dissipation. Note that both models\par
allow for a discontinuity in the plastic slip at the grain boundary. Gurtin [18] introduced a Burgers\u8217? tensor\par
at the grain boundary, analogous to the Nye\u8211?Bilby\u8211?Kr\u246?ner\u8217?s tensor for bulk crystals, to determine both the\par
interfacial energy and dissipation. One merit of this tensorial measure is that it allows the theory to satisfy the\par
slip transfer criteria. Van Beers et al. [19] proposed a similar theory that takes into account the criteria of slip\par
transfer, but differs from the formulation of Gurtin [18]. Inter-grain interaction modules from two theories are\par
compared by Gottschalk et al. [20]; Bayerschen et al. [21]. Erdle and B\u246?hlke [22] developed the continuum\par
model of dislocation/grain boundary interaction based on the micromorphic strain gradient plasticity. We also\par
mention the references [23\u8211?29] which use the same strain gradient plasticity. Similar to the CDT developed in\par
[1\u8211?3], this standard strain gradient plasticity ignores completely configurational entropy, so none of the work\par
done within this approach is consistent with thermodynamics of dislocations proposed in [4\u8211?6].\par
     The aim of this work is to model the interaction of edge dislocations with the grain boundary in polycrystals\par
within the framework of TDT. In contrast to the interaction between screw dislocations and grain boundaries\par
studied in our previous paper [10], the processes of dislocation pileup against, absorption by, and transfer\par
through the grain boundary may occur in this situation. Using the variational formulation together with the\par
proposed surface energy and dissipation potential, we will derive the interface boundary conditions for these\par
processes. The case study is carried out on the boundary conditions affecting work hardening of a bicrystal\par
subjected to plane constrained shear for three types of grain boundaries: (i) impermeable hard grain boundary,\par
(ii) grain boundary that allows dislocation transfer without absorption, and (iii) grain boundary that absorbs\par
dislocations and allows them to pass later. Note that, according to various experimental observations reported,\par
e.g., in [30,31], the grain boundary could be migrated during this dislocation absorption, but this possible\par
migration is ignored in this continuum model. We show especially the effect of dislocation absorption on work\par
hardening.\par
     The paper is organized as follows. After this brief introduction, we lay down the kinematics and thermody-\par
namic framework of TDT in Sect. 2. In Sect. 3, we analyze the effects of dissipation potential and interfacial\par
energy on the work hardening of materials and derive the conditions at the grain boundary for various processes\par
during plastic deformation. In Sect. 4, the application of the developed theory to the problem of a bicrystal\par
subjected to plane constrained shear is illustrated and its numerical treatment is presented. Detailed numerical\par
simulations are then performed and the results are discussed. We conclude the paper with a brief summary in\par
Sect. 5.\par
\par
