3.1 Interfacial energy and dissipation\par
\par
Dislocations are long-lived and well-defined defects and have various interactions with the grain boundary,\par
e.g., dislocation pileup, absorption, and transmission. Within the continuum approach, it should be possible\par
to mimic these interactions by the interfacial energy and dissipation that reflect the underlying physics at the\par
nano-/submicron scale. The low-angle grain boundary itself can be regarded as an array of dislocations [45]\par
whose interfacial energy depends on the surface dislocation density [46,47]. It also acts as an additional barrier\par
to the movement of dislocations and can later absorb or release them. Therefore, in addition to bulk dissipation,\par
interfacial dissipation must also be taken into account. In order to choose the appropriate argument for the\par
interfacial energy, the state variables of the surface must first be recognized. Although the plastic distortion and\par
the corresponding plastic slip are not the state variables in the bulk, the jump in the plastic slip representing the\par
surface dislocation density is the state variable at the grain boundary (cf. with the Burgers tensor introduced\par
in [18]). We propose the densities of interfacial energy and dissipation potential as follows\par
