4.3 Numerical implementation\par
\par
We discretize the boundary value problem formulated above by a finite difference method called the line\par
method. The latter replaces the spatial derivatives by finite differences, which allow us to transform partial\par
differential equations into a system of ordinary differential equations with respect to \u947? . We illustrate this\par
method for the case y\u771?g = h\u771?/2. For the case y\u771?g = h\u771?/2, the discretization can be done in a similar way. Let\par
the interval 0 < y\u771? < h\u771? be divided into 2n equal subintervals. Then the step in y\u771? along the grid becomes\par
\u916? y\u771? = h\u771?/2n. Because of the jump in \u946? at the interface, we distinguish the left and right nodes located at the\par
same point y\u771?g = n\u916? y\u771?. The coordinates of the nodes on the left interval 0 < y\u771? < h\u771?/2 are\par
