slip decreases gradually near the grain boundary, while it decreases more steeply to zero for a higher value\par
of k0 . Since the slope of plastic slip is proportional to the accumulated dislocation density, these distributions\par
imply that a smaller k0 leads to a larger dislocation accumulation zone and a lower accumulated density of non-\par
                                                                                           g\par
redundant dislocations near the grain boundary. This is because a small k0 makes \u961?ss small, so a lower density\par
of non-redundant dislocations is required for the backstress to have an effect on the balance of microforces.\par
The hardening behavior in the pileup process is shown in Fig. 2b. It can be seen that the hardening rate is larger\par
for smaller k0 . The reason is that the wider dislocation accumulation zone and the slower gradient increase\par
of plastic slip resulting from the small k0 lead to a higher resolved shear stress and consequently a larger\par
hardening rate. A smaller value of k0 also leads to a longer length of the accumulation phase. This is because\par
the accumulated \u961? g is relatively low for small k0 , and therefore, it takes longer to reach the required critical\par
density \u961?y .\par
