(dashed lines) in Fig. 4b. It can be seen that the tip leaves the bottom, and as the shear stress increases, the\par
discrepancy between the solid and dashed lines also increases, indicating that the groove does not stop sinking.\par
     In the pileup process, the rate of accumulated dislocation density is the highest among the different processes\par
because all dislocations are blocked by the grain boundary. When positive and negative dislocations enter the\par
grain boundary and increase the misorientation in the absorption process, the ability of the grain boundary to\par
block dislocations from transfer is enhanced, and no additional dislocations are accumulated after this process.\par
This behavior is shown in Fig. 5a. In the pileup process, the positive and negative non-redundant dislocation\par
densities are symmetrically distributed on both sides of the grain boundary, while in the absorption process, a\par
jump in the non-redundant density occurs near the grain boundary, as shown in Fig. 5b. Under the interfacial\par
condition Eq. (32), the same amount of dislocation density is shifted from one side to the other.\par
